SIMPLE: occur
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Occur
<hw>Oc*cur"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Occurred</conjf><pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Occurring</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>occurrere</ets>, <ets>occursum</ets>; <ets>ob</ets> (see
<er>Ob-</er>) + <ets>currere</ets> to run. See <er>Course</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To meet; to clash.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The resistance of the bodies they <qex>occur</qex> with.</q>
<rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To go in order to meet; to make reply.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I must <qex>occur</qex> to one specious objection.</q>
<rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To meet one's eye; to be found or met with; to
present itself; to appear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In Scripture, though the word heir <qex>occur</qex>, yet there is
no such thing as ⟦ldquo⟧heir⟦rdquo⟧ in our author's sense.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To happen; to take place; <as>as, I will write if
opportunity <ex>occurs</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To come to the mind; to arise in the mind; to
suggest itself; to be presented to the imagination or memory; -- of an
idea or thought; <as>as, it never <ex>occurred</ex> to me to call John
to ask</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>There doth not <qex>occur</qex> to me any use of this experiment
for profit.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Occurrence</ent>⟦br⟧
